</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,151,1832]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1447,1472]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Valeria Maia, for her work with plant galls and constant collection of galling thrips for study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,151,1832]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1519,1544]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Comments.</emphasis>
One of the unusual traits of this species is the sharply triangular pelta, with straight lateral margins and small lateral wings (
<figureCitation box="[442,544,1556,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 176–182" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 176–182. Holopothrips maiae sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (176) body; (177) head and pronotum; (178) mesonotum; (179) pelta; (180) spermatheca; (181) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (182) metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445232/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 179</figureCitation>
), while most 
<taxonomicName box="[707,856,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[707,856,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Holopothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have the lateral margins of pelta slightly curved or irregular, and lack basal wings. Classifying the position of the maxillary stylets (
<figureCitation box="[1167,1262,1591,1616]" captionStart="FIGURES 176–182" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 176–182. Holopothrips maiae sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (176) body; (177) head and pronotum; (178) mesonotum; (179) pelta; (180) spermatheca; (181) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (182) metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445232/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 177</figureCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1308,1411,1593,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maiae">
<emphasis box="[1308,1411,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">H. maiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult: while it is about one third of head width apart as in other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1012,1161,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1012,1161,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Holopothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with parallel stylets, the position of the stylets seems to be closer to a V-shape, thus this species might represent an intermediate state. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,378,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maiae">
<emphasis box="[151,378,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Holopothrips maiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares some similarities with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1954" box="[726,851,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Homorothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erianthi">
<emphasis box="[726,851,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">H. erianthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but males lack pore plates on sternite VI and fore wings are thoroughly pale. It is also very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[753,943,1735,1760]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spermathecus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[753,943,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">H. spermathecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[953,1019,1735,1760]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[953,1019,1735,1760]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but differs from it in the metanotal sculpture, female spermatheca not being enlarged (
<figureCitation box="[727,825,1772,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 176–182" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[182,1405,193,1951]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 176–182. Holopothrips maiae sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (176) body; (177) head and pronotum; (178) mesonotum; (179) pelta; (180) spermatheca; (181) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (182) metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445232/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 180</figureCitation>
), and the absence of a third pair of WR on abdominal tergite II.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
